SIMPLE: trow
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trow
<hw>Trow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A boat with an open well
amidships. It is used in spearing fish.</def>
<rj><au>Knight.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trow</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trow
<hw>Trow</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i. & t.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>trowen</ets>, AS. <ets>tre⟦oacute⟧wan</ets> to trust, believe, fr.
<ets>tre⟦oacute⟧w</ets> trust, <ets>tre⟦oacute⟧we</ets> true, faithful.
See <er>True</er>.]</ety> <def>To believe; to trust; to think or
suppose.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So that ye <qex>trow</qex> in Christ, and you baptize.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A better priest, I <qex>trow</qex>, there nowhere none is.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It never yet was worn, I <qex>trow</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>I trow</xex>, or <xex>trow</xex> alone, was
formerly sometimes added to questions to express contemptuous or
indignant surprise.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What tempest, I <qex>trow</qex>, threw this whale . . .
ashore?</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What is the matter, <qex>trow</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trowel</ent>⟦br⟧
